{
  "An alpha particle consists of:": "",
  "A single high-energy electron": "",
  "One proton and one neutron": "",
  "A high-energy photon with no mass": "",
  "2 protons and 2 neutrons (He-4 nucleus)": "",
  "Alpha particles are helium-4 nuclei consisting of 2 protons and 2 neutrons. They are relatively heavy, carry a +2 charge, and can be stopped by a sheet of paper or skin. In alpha decay, the parent atom loses 2 protons and 2 neutrons.": "",
  "A beta particle is:": "",
  "A positively charged proton": "",
  "A high-energy electron emitted from the nucleus": "",
  "A high-energy photon of light": "",
  "A helium nucleus with four particles": "",
  "Beta particles are high-energy electrons (beta-minus) or positrons (beta-plus) emitted from the nucleus. In beta-minus decay, a neutron converts to a proton, increasing the atomic number by 1. Beta particles can be stopped by aluminum foil.": "",
  "Gamma radiation is:": "",
  "A particle with significant mass": "",
  "A helium nucleus emitted from an atom": "",
  "An electron released from the nucleus": "",
  "High-energy electromagnetic radiation (photons)": "",
  "Gamma rays are high-energy electromagnetic radiation with no mass or charge. They are the most penetrating form of nuclear radiation, requiring thick lead or concrete to block. Gamma emission often accompanies alpha or beta decay.": "",
  "Which type of radiation has the greatest penetrating power?": "",
  "All three types are equal": "",
  "Gamma radiation is the most penetrating": "",
  "Beta radiation is the most penetrating": "",
  "Alpha radiation is the most penetrating": "",
  "Gamma radiation has the greatest penetrating power because it has no mass or charge. It can pass through most materials and requires thick lead or concrete to stop. Beta particles are moderately penetrating (stopped by aluminum), and alpha particles are the least penetrating (stopped by paper).": "",
  "Alpha particles can be stopped by:": "",
  "Thick concrete walls only": "",
  "Heavy lead shielding only": "",
  "A sheet of paper or skin": "",
  "Several centimeters of aluminum": "",
  "Alpha particles are large and heavily charged (+2), so they lose energy quickly when colliding with matter. A single sheet of paper or even a few centimeters of air is enough to stop them. Lead and concrete are needed for gamma radiation, not alpha particles.": "",
  "In alpha decay, the atomic number decreases by:": "",
  "1, because one proton is emitted": "",
  "4, because four nucleons are lost": "",
  "0, because no protons are emitted": "",
  "2, because two protons are emitted": "",
  "In alpha decay, the nucleus emits an alpha particle containing 2 protons and 2 neutrons. This decreases the atomic number by 2 (losing 2 protons) and the mass number by 4 (losing 2 protons + 2 neutrons). The element changes identity because its proton count changes.": "",
  "In beta decay, the atomic number:": "",
  "Increases by 2 as two protons form": "",
  "Decreases by 1 as a proton is lost": "",
  "Increases by 1 (neutron converts to proton)": "",
  "Stays the same as no protons change": "",
  "In beta-minus decay, a neutron in the nucleus converts into a proton and emits a beta particle (electron). This increases the atomic number by 1 because the nucleus has gained one proton, changing the element to the next one on the periodic table.": "",
  "What material is typically used to stop beta particles?": "",
  "A thin sheet of paper is sufficient": "",
  "A sheet of aluminum foil is sufficient": "",
  "Only thick lead blocks can stop them": "",
  "Only thick concrete walls can stop them": "",
  "Beta particles are lighter and smaller than alpha particles but more penetrating. They can pass through paper but are stopped by a thin sheet of aluminum or similar metal. Lead and concrete are reserved for the most penetrating radiation — gamma rays.": "",
  "In alpha decay, the mass number of the parent atom decreases by:": "",
  "1, because one nucleon is emitted": "",
  "4, because two protons and two neutrons are emitted": "",
  "0, because no mass is lost in the process": "",
  "An alpha particle consists of 2 protons and 2 neutrons, for a total of 4 nucleons. When it is emitted from the nucleus, the mass number decreases by 4 and the atomic number decreases by 2.": "",
  "Which type of radiation carries a positive charge?": "",
  "Beta particles carry a positive charge": "",
  "Gamma rays carry a positive charge": "",
  "All three types carry a positive charge": "",
  "Alpha particles carry a positive charge": "",
  "Alpha particles carry a +2 charge because they consist of 2 protons and 2 neutrons (with no electrons to balance the charge). Beta-minus particles carry a negative charge (they are electrons), and gamma rays have no charge at all since they are electromagnetic radiation.": "",
  "What is alpha decay?": "",
  "The emission of a helium-4 nucleus from an unstable atom, decreasing its atomic number by 2 and mass number by 4": "",
  "The emission of a high-energy electron from the nucleus when a neutron converts into a proton": "",
  "The release of high-energy electromagnetic radiation from a nucleus without changing its composition": "",
  "The absorption of an inner-shell electron by the nucleus, converting a proton into a neutron": "",
  "Alpha decay is a type of radioactive decay in which an unstable nucleus emits an alpha particle (helium-4 nucleus: 2 protons + 2 neutrons). This decreases the atomic number by 2 and the mass number by 4, transforming the atom into a different element.": "",
  "What is beta-minus decay?": "",
  "The emission of a helium-4 nucleus from the atom, reducing its mass number by four": "",
  "The emission of a high-energy electron from the nucleus as a neutron converts to a proton": "",
  "The release of a high-energy photon from the nucleus with no change to atomic or mass number": "",
  "The capture of an orbiting electron by the nucleus, reducing the atomic number by one": "",
  "Beta-minus decay occurs when a neutron in the nucleus converts to a proton and emits a high-energy electron (beta particle). The atomic number increases by 1, but the mass number stays the same because the total number of nucleons has not changed.": "",
  "Define gamma radiation in the context of nuclear decay.": "",
  "A stream of helium nuclei released from a heavy atom undergoing radioactive decay": "",
  "A stream of high-energy electrons emitted when neutrons convert to protons in the nucleus": "",
  "High-energy electromagnetic radiation emitted from a nucleus, with no mass and no charge": "",
  "Low-energy visible light released when electrons drop to lower energy levels in atoms": "",
  "Gamma radiation consists of high-energy photons (electromagnetic radiation) emitted from an excited nucleus. It has no mass and no charge, which is why it is the most penetrating form of radiation. Gamma emission does not change the atomic number or mass number of the atom.": "",
  "What is the term 'penetrating power' referring to in radiation?": "",
  "The speed at which radiation particles travel through empty space or a vacuum": "",
  "The amount of energy that a radioactive source releases over a specific time period": "",
  "The number of atoms that are affected by a single radioactive decay event in a sample": "",
  "The ability of radiation to pass through materials, which depends on its mass and charge": "",
  "Penetrating power refers to how far radiation can travel through matter before being absorbed or stopped. It depends on the mass, charge, and energy of the radiation. Alpha has low penetrating power (stopped by paper), beta is moderate (stopped by aluminum), and gamma is high (requires thick lead or concrete).": "",
  "What is meant by 'radioactive decay'?": "",
  "The spontaneous emission of particles or energy from an unstable nucleus to become more stable": "",
  "The process of splitting a heavy nucleus into two lighter nuclei using a neutron bombardment": "",
  "The combining of two light nuclei under extreme heat and pressure to form a heavier one": "",
  "The breaking of chemical bonds in a molecule when it is exposed to ultraviolet light energy": "",
  "Radioactive decay is the spontaneous process by which an unstable atomic nucleus loses energy by emitting particles or electromagnetic radiation. The nucleus transforms to become more stable. This can happen through alpha decay, beta decay, or gamma emission.": "",
  "What is the 'atomic number' and how does it change during alpha decay?": "",
  "The atomic number is the total number of nucleons; it decreases by 4 during alpha decay": "",
  "The atomic number is the number of protons; it decreases by 2 during alpha decay": "",
  "The atomic number is the number of electrons; it stays the same during alpha decay": "",
  "The atomic number is the number of neutrons; it increases by 1 during alpha decay": "",
  "The atomic number equals the number of protons in the nucleus and defines the element's identity. In alpha decay, 2 protons are lost (as part of the alpha particle), so the atomic number decreases by 2 and the atom becomes a different element.": "",
  "What is the 'mass number' of an atom?": "",
  "The total number of electrons orbiting the nucleus of that atom": "",
  "The weight of the atom measured on a laboratory scale in grams": "",
  "The total number of protons and neutrons (nucleons) in the nucleus": "",
  "The number of energy levels that the atom has filled with electrons": "",
  "The mass number (A) is the total count of protons plus neutrons in the nucleus. It appears as the superscript in nuclear notation. During alpha decay, the mass number decreases by 4; during beta decay, the mass number stays the same.": "",
  "Define the term 'ionizing radiation.'": "",
  "Radiation that produces visible light when it passes through a glass prism": "",
  "Radiation that only affects metallic materials but not organic tissue": "",
  "Radiation that has no effect on the atoms or molecules it encounters": "",
  "Radiation with enough energy to remove electrons from atoms, creating ions": "",
  "Ionizing radiation has enough energy to knock electrons off atoms, creating charged ions. Alpha, beta, and gamma radiation are all forms of ionizing radiation. This ability to ionize atoms is what makes nuclear radiation potentially harmful to living tissue.": "",
  "What is a 'daughter nucleus' in radioactive decay?": "",
  "The new nucleus that is produced after the parent nucleus undergoes radioactive decay": "",
  "The original unstable nucleus before it emits any radiation or particles at all": "",
  "The alpha particle or beta particle that is emitted during the decay process": "",
  "The gamma ray photon that is released along with other particles during decay": "",
  "In radioactive decay, the original unstable atom is called the 'parent nucleus' and the new atom produced after decay is called the 'daughter nucleus.' The daughter nucleus has a different number of protons or neutrons than the parent.": "",
  "What is the relationship between radiation charge and penetrating power?": "",
  "Charged radiation has greater penetrating power because it attracts surrounding electrons": "",
  "Radiation with more mass and charge interacts more with matter and has lower penetrating power": "",
  "All types of radiation penetrate matter equally regardless of their mass or charge values": "",
  "Only uncharged radiation can penetrate matter because charged particles are always reflected": "",
  "Radiation with more mass and charge (like alpha particles: heavy, +2 charge) interacts strongly with matter, losing energy quickly and thus having low penetrating power. Gamma rays have no mass or charge, so they interact less and penetrate much further. Beta particles fall in between.": "",
  "A student is working with three radioactive sources in a lab. Source A is blocked by paper, Source B passes through paper but is blocked by aluminum, and Source C passes through both. What types of radiation are A, B, and C?": "",
  "A is gamma, B is beta, and C is alpha radiation": "",
  "A is beta, B is alpha, and C is gamma radiation": "",
  "A is alpha, B is gamma, and C is beta radiation": "",
  "A is alpha, B is beta, and C is gamma radiation": "",
  "Alpha particles are stopped by paper (Source A), beta particles pass through paper but are stopped by aluminum (Source B), and gamma rays pass through both paper and aluminum, requiring thick lead or concrete to stop (Source C). This order reflects increasing penetrating power.": "",
  "A scientist observes that after a decay event, an atom of element X has become an atom of an element with 2 fewer protons. What type of decay occurred?": "",
  "Beta decay occurred, since a neutron converted to a proton": "",
  "Gamma decay occurred, releasing a high-energy photon from the nucleus": "",
  "Alpha decay occurred, since an alpha particle (2 protons, 2 neutrons) was emitted": "",
  "Electron capture occurred, since the nucleus absorbed an inner electron": "",
  "When an atom loses 2 protons, it has undergone alpha decay. The alpha particle emitted contains 2 protons and 2 neutrons, reducing the atomic number by 2 and the mass number by 4. Gamma decay does not change the atomic number, and beta decay changes it by 1.": "",
  "In a nuclear medicine department, a technician must choose shielding for different radiation sources. Which shielding correctly matches each radiation type?": "",
  "Paper for gamma, aluminum for alpha, and lead for beta radiation": "",
  "Lead for alpha, paper for beta, and aluminum for gamma radiation": "",
  "Aluminum for alpha, lead for beta, and concrete for gamma radiation": "",
  "Paper for alpha, aluminum for beta, and thick lead for gamma radiation": "",
  "The correct shielding for each type: alpha particles are stopped by paper, beta particles are stopped by aluminum, and gamma rays require thick lead or concrete. Using the right shielding is essential for safety in medical and industrial settings.": "",
  "A researcher discovers that a sample of carbon-14 has undergone beta decay. What element has the carbon-14 become?": "",
  "It becomes boron-14, with one fewer proton than carbon": "",
  "It becomes nitrogen-14, with one more proton than carbon": "",
  "It remains carbon-14 since beta decay does not change the element": "",
  "It becomes carbon-10 by losing 4 units of mass number": "",
  "In beta-minus decay, a neutron converts to a proton and an electron is emitted. Carbon-14 has 6 protons. After beta decay, it has 7 protons, making it nitrogen-14. The mass number stays at 14 because the total number of nucleons has not changed.": "",
  "A student handling radioactive materials is told that alpha emitters are safe outside the body but dangerous if inhaled or ingested. Why is this the case?": "",
  "Alpha particles can pass through the body from outside but not from inside tissue": "",
  "Alpha particles convert to gamma rays once they enter the body and become more harmful": "",
  "Alpha particles cannot penetrate skin externally, but inside the body they directly damage nearby cells": "",
  "Alpha particles are only radioactive when they come in contact with water inside the body": "",
  "Alpha particles have low penetrating power and cannot pass through skin. However, if alpha-emitting materials are inhaled or ingested, the particles directly irradiate internal tissues at close range. Their heavy mass and high charge cause significant ionization damage to nearby cells.": "",
  "A nuclear physicist observes an atom of uranium-238 undergo alpha decay. What are the atomic number and mass number of the daughter nucleus?": "",
  "Atomic number 93 and mass number 238": "",
  "Atomic number 90 and mass number 234": "",
  "Atomic number 92 and mass number 234": "",
  "Atomic number 88 and mass number 230": "",
  "Uranium-238 has atomic number 92 and mass number 238. After alpha decay (losing 2 protons and 2 neutrons), the daughter nucleus has atomic number 90 (92 - 2) and mass number 234 (238 - 4). This is thorium-234.": "",
  "In a hospital, a patient undergoes a procedure using a gamma-emitting isotope. Why is gamma radiation preferred for medical imaging over alpha or beta radiation?": "",
  "Gamma rays are the least harmful type of radiation and cause no damage to tissues at all": "",
  "Gamma rays can exit the body to be detected by external cameras due to their high penetrating power": "",
  "Gamma rays are cheaper to produce than alpha or beta radiation in laboratory settings": "",
  "Gamma rays travel slower than alpha or beta particles, making them easier to track with sensors": "",
  "Gamma rays are used in medical imaging because their high penetrating power allows them to pass through the body and be detected by external cameras or scanners. Alpha and beta particles would be absorbed by body tissues before they could escape to be detected.": "",
  "A student writes a nuclear equation for beta decay of potassium-40. The daughter element should have what atomic number compared to potassium (Z = 19)?": "",
  "Atomic number 17, two less than potassium": "",
  "Atomic number 19, the same as potassium": "",
  "Atomic number 20, one more than potassium": "",
  "Atomic number 21, two more than potassium": "",
  "In beta-minus decay, a neutron converts to a proton. This increases the atomic number by 1. Potassium has atomic number 19, so after beta decay the daughter element has atomic number 20, which is calcium. The mass number remains 40.": "",
  "A lab technician notices that a radiation detector shows no change in count rate when a sheet of paper is placed between the source and detector, but the count drops significantly with aluminum foil. What type of radiation is the source most likely emitting?": "",
  "The source is most likely emitting alpha radiation": "",
  "The source is most likely emitting gamma radiation": "",
  "The source is most likely emitting beta radiation": "",
  "The source is emitting both alpha and gamma radiation": "",
  "Since paper does not reduce the count but aluminum does, the source is emitting beta particles. Alpha particles would have been stopped by the paper, and gamma rays would pass through both paper and aluminum. Beta particles pass through paper but are absorbed by aluminum.": "",
  "A chemistry teacher demonstrates that a smoke detector contains americium-241, which emits alpha particles. A student asks why this is safe for a home device. What is the best explanation?": "",
  "Americium-241 is not actually radioactive when used in small quantities in devices": "",
  "The alpha particles are converted to harmless light energy before leaving the device": "",
  "Smoke detectors use such a tiny amount that the alpha particles are fully contained within the device housing": "",
  "Alpha particles are completely harmless to humans regardless of the amount present": "",
  "Smoke detectors use a very small amount of americium-241. Alpha particles have extremely low penetrating power — they cannot even pass through the plastic housing of the device. As long as the device is intact and the material is not inhaled or ingested, it poses no health risk.": ""
}